Thanks

You could avoid this kind of resetting behaviour with `mock.patch`. Something like the following:

```python
from mock import patch
@patch('SSMParameter.BOTO3_SESSION_FACTORY', new=session_factory)
@patch('SSMParameter. BOTO3_CLIENT_FACTORY', new=client_factory)
def test_session_factory(self):
    # your tests here (without any [re-]set)
```

(patch will automatically patch the class attributes and reset them after that individual test)

I suggest setting an error message based upon the exception type and then having a check to see if the error message has been set and return a HttpResponse like so ->

```
if error:
       return HttpResponse(error, status=401)
```

Then I don't understand the generated c code correctly.
Tried to annotate to my understanding:
```c
        //Copy env
        struct SN_env env2 = * z; /* $ s, line 5 */
        // Set current value to S[0] = 'foo'
        z->p = z->S[0];
        z->lb = z->c = 0;
        z->l = SIZE(z->p);
        {   int ret;
            {   int saved_c = z->c;
                // Set current value to 'bar'
                ret =insert_s(z, z->c, z->l, 3, s_1); /* =, line 5 */
                z->c = saved_c;
            }
            if (ret < 0) return ret;
        }
        {
            //Copy env
            struct SN_env env3 = * z; /* $ t, line 5 */
            //Set current value to S[1] = '1'
            z->p = z->S[1];
            z->lb = z->c = 0;
            z->l = SIZE(z->p);
            {   int ret;
                {   int saved_c = z->c;
                    // Set current value to S[0] (currently still 'foo')
                    ret =insert_v(z, z->c, z->l, z->S[0]); /* = s, line 5 */
                    z->c = saved_c;
                }
                if (ret < 0) return ret;
            }
            failure = 0; /* mark success */
            // Set S[1] = current value = 'foo'
            z->S[1] = z->p;
            // Reset env and thus current value to 'bar'
            * z = env3;
            if (failure) goto lab1;
        }
        failure = 0; /* mark success */
    lab1:
        //Set S[0] to current value 'bar'
        z->S[0] = z->p;
        //Reset env
        * z = env2;
```

What I probably get wrong is how pointers are handled.
```c
 z->p = z->S[0];
```
Makes `z->p` point to `z->S[0]`. So if `z->p` is changed `z->S[0]` is changed too, correct?
But then, the reset would be useless:
```c
z->S[0] = z->p;
```

Possible solutions:

1. One way to get the intended behaviour is to special case string variable assignments (this would involve work in the tokenizer and analyzer and probably the other backend which is probably not feasable).

2. Another way would be to hack up the rust implementation to use mutable pointers like the C implemenation (IMO we should avoid that).

3. Or we keep a field in the generator to what string variable the env is currently set.  
Then in `generate_assignfrom` not only the `env` could be assigned to but also the string variable.
(This would involve adding a new field to the generator struct)

I personally favor option 3 but am not sure if I understand the consequences of introducing a new field to the generator struct.

As a followup, just above this section, there is:

    {{ if ne $useSSL "false" }}

This is the reason I had used this method of comparison, the other similar references in this template used this same "trick". Is it idiomatic? Is it necessary? If the bare case works, I'm fine with the clearer expression.

CLI does not support iterator, change this to:
```python
if resource_group_name:
     result = racf.appliances.list_by_resource_group(resource_group_name)
else:
     result = racf.appliances.list_by_subscription()
return list(result)
```

@johanste should be documented? Twice issues like this today.

@roopahc just pointed out that the parent (wrapped) class' produce() method has nearly an identical order:

http://docs.confluent.io/3.0.1/clients/confluent-kafka-python/index.html#confluent_kafka.Producer.produce

Seems like keeping it as-is actually matches best with what's already there...

`strcmp(tp_name, "bool_")` also looks like a pretty nice simplification. In that case the separate `np.bool_` logic could be removed completely and just leave:
```c++
else if (convert || strcmp(tp_name, "bool_") == 0) {
    ...
}
```
